     1	MacKenzie Scott’s giving, in QALYs
     2	An evidence-weighted, auditable cost-effectiveness model of a $26 billion portfolio
     3	
     4	Max Ghenis∗
     5	
     6	MacKenzie Scott has disclosed $26.39 billion in gifts to more than 2,500 organizations since 2019 — her 2025 giving alone was about a third of the value of that year’s
     7	U.S. megagifts — yet almost none of it is denominated in outcomes. This paper prices
     8	the entire portfolio in quality-adjusted life-years. A Monte Carlo model allocates
     9	dollars across 14 intervention archetypes using Scott’s own gift-level database, imputes
    10	the undisclosed third from recipients’ pre-gift IRS 990 revenue, assigns each archetype
    11	a cost-per-QALY anchor from published causal estimates, and shrinks every effect
    12	toward zero in proportion to the causal credibility of its evidence. The best-guess
    13	estimate is a median of roughly 202,000 QALYs (90% interval 94,000–419,000), a
    14	blended $150,000 per QALY, and a median benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 under the valuation distribution HHS uses for regulatory analysis. Three findings follow. First,
    15	estimated impact is geographically concentrated: the 4.8% of dollars funding health
    16	and development delivered outside the United States, priced at global-health anchors,
    17	accounts for 69% of estimated health impact. Second, gift size scales with recipient
    18	size to only the 0.41 power — a 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more
    19	money. Third, the answer is dominated by evidence philosophy rather than arithmetic:
    20	restricting credit almost entirely to randomized evidence collapses the median to
    21	~9,000 QALYs while taking every study at near face value raises it to ~415,000 — a
    22	45× range, larger than the spread from any single distributional parameter tested.
    23	All parameters, code, data snapshots, and an AI-audit trail are public, and the model
    24	runs interactively in the browser.
    25	Source: Article Notebook
    26	
    27	1 Introduction
    28	MacKenzie Scott gave away $7.17 billion in 2025 (Huddleston 2025); Giving USA counts $6.65
    29	billion of it against $19.2 billion in U.S. megagift dollars — about a third of that year’s megagift
    30	value (Indiana University Lilly Family School of Philanthropy 2026; Gamboa 2026). (The bases
    31	differ: Yield Giving’s own annual total is the larger figure.) Her disclosed lifetime total is $26.39
    32	∗
    33	
    34	max@maxghenis.com. I am CEO of PolicyEngine and president of the Axiom Foundation; this paper is a personal
    35	research project and does not represent the views of either organization. Neither I nor the organizations I lead
    36	have received funding from MacKenzie Scott or Yield Giving. Interactive version, code, data, and full audit
    37	trail: https://maxghenis.com/mackenzie-scott-qaly and https://github.com/MaxGhenis/mackenzie-scott-qaly.
    38	
    39	1
    40	
    41	billion across 2,711 gifts to 2,545 organizations since 2019 (Yield Giving 2026). Almost none of
    42	it is denominated in health, and, to my knowledge, no published estimate prices the portfolio in
    43	outcomes of any kind.
    44	This paper does so in the unit health economists use to compare a death averted against years
    45	lived in better health: the quality-adjusted life-year. The exercise is deliberately in the style
    46	of a charity evaluator’s cost-effectiveness analysis (GiveWell 2026), scaled from a program to a
    47	portfolio, with one addition the setting forces: because most of the portfolio funds interventions
    48	whose health effects have never been causally measured, the model makes its epistemics explicit.
    49	Every effect is shrunk toward zero in proportion to how well its supporting study identifies
    50	causation, the shrinkage schedule is a slider rather than a buried constant, and the headline
    51	is reported across the full range of evidence philosophies — from counting only randomized
    52	evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
    53	The paper makes four contributions. It provides what I believe is the first outside, portfolio-level
    54	cost-effectiveness estimate of an individual mega-donor’s disclosed lifetime giving — funder-run
    55	portfolio metrics exist, including GiveWell’s aggregate impact estimates (GiveWell 2026), Robin
    56	Hood’s benefit–cost framework (Robin Hood Foundation 2025), the Constellation Fund’s portfolio
    57	reporting (Constellation Fund 2025), and social-rate-of-return analysis of USAID’s Development
    58	Innovation Ventures portfolio (Center for Effective Global Action 2023); the difference here is
    59	independence from the donor, a subject who publishes no outcome data, and explicit evidence
    60	weighting: a best-guess median of 202,000 QALYs from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in
    61	2026 dollars), a blended $150,067 per QALY, and a median benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 under the
    62	HHS regulatory value-per-QALY distribution (Kearsley 2026). It estimates extreme geographic
    63	concentration of impact under its pricing assumptions: the 4.8% of dollars funding global health
    64	and development delivered outside the United States accounts for 69.1% of estimated health
    65	impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the gift data itself: across 1,313 disclosed
    66	gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift revenue to the power 0.41 (R² 0.37) —
    67	Scott’s giving is far flatter across organization size than proportional. And it demonstrates a
    68	working method for auditable, AI-assisted cost-effectiveness modeling: the model was built with
    69	a frontier language model, reviewed and corrected in public across eleven revision rounds, audited
    70	by two independent model families against primary filings, and ships with versioned parameters,
    71	machine-checked citations, and a browser implementation that reruns the full Monte Carlo under
    72	any reader’s assumptions.
    73	The unit of account deserves a caveat before any number. QALYs measure health. Most of Scott’s
    74	portfolio aims at other things — education, economic mobility, equity, civic infrastructure —
    75	whose primary benefits are not health benefits. A finding that a dollar of education philanthropy
    76	produces few QALYs is a statement about the lens, not a verdict on the gift. The estimates
    77	are a partial, health-only accounting under positive-effect priors — not a lower bound on total
    78	wellbeing: the lens omits the primary intended benefits of most of the portfolio, and the model
    79	places no probability on zero or harmful effects, a structural choice the limitations section returns
    80	to.
    81	
    82	2
    83	
    84	2 Data
    85	2.1 The ledger
    86	Scott’s essays disclose giving in dated tranches totaling $26.39 billion nominal over 2020–2025.
    87	The model inflates each tranche to 2026 dollars with CPI-U, so dollars and cost-effectiveness
    88	evidence share one price level: $30.3B total. All derivations below, and the replication repository,
    89	start from a verbatim snapshot of the Yield Giving gift database retrieved July 11, 2026 (Yield
    90	Giving 2026).
    91	
    92	2.2 Allocation across causes
    93	Scott publishes no aggregate dollars-by-cause breakdown, but she publishes something more
    94	granular: a gift-level database listing every recipient organization, its self-reported focus areas,
    95	and — for 2,035 of 2,711 gifts ($17.46B, about two-thirds of the nominal total) — the dollar
    96	amount. Each organization’s dollars are split equally across its focus areas; the database’s
    97	53 areas map onto the model’s 14 intervention archetypes under a documented, sync-tested
    98	crosswalk.
    99	The undisclosed third is imputed rather than dropped. Because the essays give each year’s
   100	total, the undisclosed residual per period is a known dollar amount; it is distributed across that
   101	period’s undisclosed gifts in proportion to each recipient’s pre-gift IRS Form 990 total revenue
   102	(ProPublica 2026), raised to an elasticity fit on the disclosed pairs. Pre-gift means the latest
   103	filing strictly before the gift year, since a Scott gift mechanically inflates receipt-year revenue.
   104	The fit is a finding in its own right: across 1,313 disclosed gift–filing pairs, log gift size rises
   105	with log revenue with slope 0.41 (R² 0.37). A 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more
   106	money, not 10× more. The fit is descriptive and conditional: it is estimated on disclosed gifts
   107	with a matched pre-gift filing (1,313 of 2,035 disclosed and 2,711 total gifts), treats repeated
   108	gifts to an organization as independent, and pools years; 287 of the 676 undisclosed gifts lack
   109	a usable filing and receive their period’s median weight. It is a within-sample regularity used
   110	for imputation, not a validated prediction rule. Fuzzy name-to-EIN matches were audited by
   111	a third, smaller model against the live IRS API, with corrections committed as a reviewable
   112	overlay. The imputed third moves each cause share by at most about 1.5 percentage points —
   113	under the imputation model, the disclosed two-thirds is representative.
   114	
   115	2.3 Delivery geography
   116	Each organization reports service locations. Weighting disclosed dollars by the audited share of
   117	each organization’s locations outside the United States, an estimated 19% of disclosed dollars
   118	($3.34B of $17.46B) sits with organizations reporting non-U.S. service locations — 20.4% under
   119	the raw rule that counts a bare “global” listing as fully non-U.S. — led by environment, health,
   120	and funding intermediaries. Locations are an equal-split proxy: a listed location is not an
   121	expenditure share, and no organization reports how Scott’s own gift was deployed. The model
   122	prices geography through a single channel: health-relevant dollars route to a global-health
   123	archetype in proportion to the recipient’s non-U.S. service share, because global health delivery
   124	
   125	3
   126	
   127	is the one category with a published cost-per-QALY evidence base an order of magnitude below
   128	U.S. anchors. Education and climate dollars keep their U.S.-study anchors wherever they are
   129	delivered; if geography changes their effectiveness, the model does not capture it.
   130	The coarsest geographic field is the bare label “global.” An audit of the 50 organizations with
   131	the most dollars attached to that label — 87% of its dollars; 20 of the 50 also list other locations
   132	— replaced the blanket assumption of fully-abroad delivery with fractions coded independently
   133	by two model families from each organization’s filings and program reports, then reconciled (33
   134	agreements within tolerance; four adjudicated to documented filings arithmetic; the remainder
   135	averaged), with per-organization sources and confidence grades — 16 high, 17 medium, 17 low —
   136	committed to the repository. Many “global” organizations operate substantially in the United
   137	States: Planned Parenthood and Crisis Text Line, for example, list “global” service but are
   138	roughly 95% and 93% U.S. in their most recent organization-wide reporting — later-period
   139	proxies for how earlier gifts were deployed, since neither reports gift-level allocation. The audited
   140	allocation routes 4.82% of the ledger to the global health and development archetype. That
   141	routed bucket is itself mixed: its dollars sit 42% in Sub-Saharan Africa, 20% in South Asia, and
   142	11% in Latin America, but 18% is unattributable multi-region activity and roughly 4% sits in
   143	high-income regions — all priced at the same low-and-middle-income anchors, a coarseness the
   144	limitations section flags.
   145	
   146	3 Model
   147	Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the
   148	derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in
   149	published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. Causal
   150	credibility asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification
   185	model conversion, not a GiveWell QALY figure), modeled as loguniform $150–$260, sharing each
   186	draw’s realization multiplier, and receiving RCT-grade credibility — the strongest tier — where
   187	portfolio archetypes receive their own.
   188	
   189	4 Results
   190	Source: Article Notebook
   191	Source: Article Notebook
   192	
   193	At the best-guess defaults (100,000 draws), the portfolio produces a median of 201,923 QALYs,
   194	with a 90% interval of 94,000 to 419,000 and a mean of 222,060. The interval is a probabilisticsensitivity range under the stated priors, not a confidence interval; Monte Carlo error on the
   195	median is a few hundred QALYs. The blended cost-effectiveness — dollars given over QALYs
   196	produced, at the median — is $150,067 per QALY. Monetized under the value-per-QALY
   197	distribution HHS recommends for regulatory analysis (central $726,000 at 3%; Kearsley (2026),
   198	Table 3), the median draw-level benefit–cost ratio is 4.9 (90% interval 2.1–11.0, reflecting both
   199	health-output and valuation uncertainty). Figure 1 shows the full distribution.
   200	
   201	4.1 Where it comes from
   202	Table 1 decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper’s central contrast: the
   203	global health and development slice — 4.8% of dollars — contributes 69.1% of estimated QALYs,
   204	at a modeled cost of about $9,477 per QALY against $75,673–$305,164 for the causes with
   205	quasi-experimental or better U.S. evidence. The 1,278-fold spread in modeled cost-effectiveness
   206	within a single donor’s portfolio, under stipulated priors, is partly the lens speaking — its low
   207	end is dominated by assumption-tier buckets whose near-zero credibility is an input, and whose
   208	main benefits QALYs do not count — but the spread among evidenced health buckets alone
   209	exceeds an order of magnitude, restating in one column an empirical regularity long emphasized
   210	in the effective-altruism literature (Ord 2013): the cheapest health in the world is not bought
   211	where most philanthropic dollars are spent.
   212	Source: Article Notebook
